{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5e73d7b5-2407-415c-a3da-8c361f824911","content":"With **MSTest 3.8.2** on .NET 9, the recommended pattern is:\n\n- **`TestContext`** — use a property with `{ get; set; }` (auto-populated by the framework)\n- **Sync init** — constructor or `[TestInitialize]`\n- **Async init** — make `[TestInitialize]` return `Task`\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly MyService _service;\n\n    // TestContext injected automatically via property\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; set; } = null!;\n\n    // Sync initialization (constructor)\n    public MyTests()\n    {\n        _service = new MyService();\n    }\n\n    // Async initialization\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.ConnectAsync();\n        TestContext.WriteLine(\"Initialized\");\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_service);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- The constructor runs first (sync setup), then `[TestInitialize]` runs (async setup)\n- `TestContext` is set *before* `[TestInitialize]`, so it's safe to use there — but it's **not** available in the constructor\n- Use `[ClassInitialize]` / `[ClassCleanup]` (both support `async Task`) for one-time class-level setup","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9b3d69cd-2c29-4ea0-9e8d-89c1f9322a4c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is using MSTest 3.8.2 with .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or the `TestContext` property. In MSTest v3+, constructor injection is supported.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` method.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: `[TestInitialize]` supports async methods (returning `Task`).\n\nActually, let me think about the modern MSTest approach more carefully:\n\nIn MSTest v3+:\n- `TestContext` can be injected via constructor (this is the modern way)\n\n\n- `[TestInitialize]` supports both sync and async methods\n- You can also use `[ClassInitialize]` for class-level setup\n\nThe recommended modern approach in MSTest 3.x is to inject `TestContext` via a property that the framework auto-sets, and use `[TestInitialize]` for setup logic. However, you can only have one `[TestInitialize]` method, so if you need both sync and async initialization, you'd need to combine them into a single async method or use separate initialization patterns.\n\nActually, let me clarify the right approach here. In MSTest 3.8.2, `TestContext` is available through property injection, and constructor injection is also supported in newer versions. The cleanest way to handle both sync and async initialization is to do synchronous work in the constructor and async work in an `[TestInitialize]` method that returns a `Task`, or consolidate everything into a single async `[TestInitialize]` method.","outputTokens":874,"requestId":"D005:1D248C:15C43D3:192BA03:69EC1773"},"id":"3d93957f-4082-4d32-8eff-9906b1aab4b0","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:23:17.240Z","parentId":"ef03dfb2-b086-489e-a835-e9fb3fce3bb8"}
